element_texts.text:
Rosebud, S. Dak.
May 22 1903
My dear Uncle
I will send you Tomorrow
twenty six nd drawings, some of the
heads there are three and four but
different positions. I have got 
twenty oil portraits finished. I have
not been working too hard.
Chief Sorrel Horse is sitting for one
now he has the reputation of stealing
more horses from other tribes of Indian than any Indian he like very much
to tell about it.
I will send the oil portraits to
my Father as he has a lot of my
Indian frames and he can just as
well frame them for me.
I hardly know what my plans

are for the Summer it is too lat to work during unclear and the Indians do not like to sit.
These Indians do pretty? well in the Summer they are hired at a $1.50 a day to fix the wagon roads? all Summer The result is the roads? and bridges are in good condition and then? it gives employment to the Indians, it unclear be a good idea I think if all reservations would do this.
Tell Aunt Emma I received unclear unclear from Munich.
Love to you both
Your affectionate nephew
Elbridge.
4218
